Ranking of Storm Events’ Effects on Population Health and Economy

2023-03-09

Synopsis

Storm data from 1950 through November 2011 were downloaded from the NOAA Storm Database and investigated regarding which types of events cause the most human (injuries and death) and economic damage, without regard to locality or timing. It was notable that the “Event Type” (EVTYPE) contains very messy data, many alternate spellings and different names for possibly the same event types. It is unclear whether the audience needs to know about the total damage per event type, which is highly skewed by the number of events per category (Fig. 1), so results are presented both as totals and as per-event values.
In terms of human damage, tornadoes have the highest impact in both injuries and deaths, whereas one event each which were “UNSEASONABLY WARM AND DRY” and “Heat Wave” had the highest impacts per individual event. In terms of total economic damage, FLOOD has the highest impact on property damage DROUGHT has the highest impact on crop damage. Again one event each had the highest impact on a per-event basis: “HEAVY RAIN/SEVERE WEATHER” on property damage and “EXCESSIVE WETNESS” on crop damage.

The “EXP” columns have a lot of messy data. I will convert what’s obvious (lower case to upper case for k and m will be handled when converting to total dollars), and the remainder will be ignored. “H/h” may refer to hundreds, but there are only 7 entries, and are not likely to contribute meaningfully to the most costly events.

Transformations

I will remove all rows where there are no injuries, deaths, or economic damage. In addition, I will add 2 columns to transform the economic damage into dollars. property will conditionally multiply PROPDMG based on the modifier in PROPDMGEXP, and similarly, crop will conditionally multiply PROPDMG based on the modifier in PROPDMGEXP.

stormData <- stormDataRaw %>% 
     filter(FATALITIES > 0 | INJURIES > 0 | CROPDMG > 0 | PROPDMG >0) %>%
     mutate(property = case_when(
          PROPDMGEXP == 'K' ~ PROPDMG * 1000,
          PROPDMGEXP == 'k' ~ PROPDMG * 1000,
          PROPDMGEXP == 'M' ~ PROPDMG * 1000000,
          PROPDMGEXP == 'm' ~ PROPDMG * 1000000,
          PROPDMGEXP == 'B' ~ PROPDMG * 1000000000,
          TRUE ~ PROPDMG
     )) %>%
     mutate(crop = case_when(
          CROPDMGEXP == 'K' ~ CROPDMG * 1000,
          CROPDMGEXP == 'k' ~ CROPDMG * 1000,
          CROPDMGEXP == 'M' ~ CROPDMG * 1000000,
          CROPDMGEXP == 'm' ~ CROPDMG * 1000000,
          CROPDMGEXP == 'B' ~ CROPDMG * 1000000000,
          TRUE ~ CROPDMG
     ))

Make a table which summarizes by EVTYPE, including total bodily and economic damages, as well as each of those values averaged per event by event type. Without this transformation, large numbers in the data could be confounded by large numbers of events.
Transform EVDATA into a factor with levels that scale with the number of events of each type.
In addition, add columns to scale the values as percent of total, allowing all events to be plotted on the same graph. Then melt the scaled data into a longer table.
Finally, filter the rows to contain only those event types which contribute to at least 1% of their respective damage.

groupedStormData <- stormData %>% group_by(EVTYPE) %>% 
     summarize(n=n(), FatPerEvent = mean(FATALITIES), Fatalities = sum(FATALITIES),
              InjPerEvent = mean(INJURIES), raw.injuries = sum(INJURIES),
              PropDamPerEvent = mean(property), PropertyDamage = sum(property),
              CropDamPerEvent = mean(crop), CropDamage = sum(crop)) %>%
     ## scale all columns to % of total
     mutate(Deaths.Per.Event = FatPerEvent/sum(FatPerEvent),
          Deaths = Fatalities/sum(Fatalities)    ,
          Injuries.Per.Event = InjPerEvent/sum(InjPerEvent),
          Injuries = raw.injuries/sum(raw.injuries),
          Property.Damage.per.event = PropDamPerEvent/sum(PropDamPerEvent),
          Property.Damage = PropertyDamage/sum(PropertyDamage),
          Crop.Damage.per.Event = CropDamPerEvent/sum(CropDamPerEvent),
          Crop.Damage = CropDamage/sum(CropDamage)
          ) %>%
     arrange(n)

## make EVTYPE a factor with levels relative to the current sort by frequency
groupedStormData$EVTYPE <- factor(groupedStormData$EVTYPE, levels = groupedStormData$EVTYPE)


## transform table to long so multiple categories can be in the same bar
## Make 2 tables one for human damage (injuries, fatalities) and other economic
longHumanStormData <- groupedStormData %>% pivot_longer(
     cols = c("Deaths.Per.Event","Deaths","Injuries.Per.Event","Injuries"),
     names_to = "Damage.Type", values_to = "value")
longHumanStormData$Damage.Type <- as.factor(longHumanStormData$Damage.Type)
longEconStormData <- groupedStormData %>% pivot_longer(
     cols = c("Property.Damage.per.event","Crop.Damage.per.Event","Property.Damage","Crop.Damage"),
     names_to = "Damage.Type", values_to = "value")
longEconStormData$Damage.Type <- as.factor(longEconStormData$Damage.Type)
## limit data to only events with damage that accounts for 1% of category
longHumanStormData <- longHumanStormData %>% filter(value>0.01)
longEconStormData <- longEconStormData %>% filter(value>0.01)

Results

The first figure shows both injuries and fatalities by event type, including all data showing any damage. The X axis includes all event types, and is ranked from least common on the left to most common on the right. The top figures are totals, and the bottom figures are averaged per event type to account for any bias introduces with high frequency events. X axis is the same on all plots.

# 1 Total Fatalities
p <- ggplot(groupedStormData, aes(EVTYPE, y=Fatalities))
p + geom_col(color = "blue") + labs(y = "Fatalities per Event Category",
         x = "Event Type, ranked by frequency") + 
     scale_x_discrete(guide = NULL) 
# 2 Total Injuries
q <- ggplot(groupedStormData, aes(EVTYPE, y=Injuries))
q + geom_col(color = "blue") + labs(y = "Injuries per Event Category",
         x = "Event Type, ranked by frequency") + 
     scale_x_discrete(guide = NULL) 
# 3 Fatalities per Event
r <- ggplot(groupedStormData, aes(EVTYPE, y=FatPerEvent))
r + geom_col(color = "blue") + labs(y = "Fatalities per Event",
         x = "Event Type, ranked by frequency") + 
     scale_x_discrete(guide = NULL) 
# 4 Injuries per Event
s <- ggplot(groupedStormData, aes(EVTYPE, y=InjPerEvent))
s + geom_col(color = "blue") + labs(y = "Injuries per Event",
         x = "Event Type, ranked by frequency") + 
     scale_x_discrete(guide = NULL)

Figure 1 (above). Exploratory Analysis of Storm Effects on Human Health

It’s unclear whether the audience wants to know the total damage that’s been done by an event type or the predicted damage for a single event. I have plotted both on the following figures. To reduce noise from so many event categories, for all types of damage, I included only events that represent at least 1% of the damage for that category.

f <- ggplot(longHumanStormData, aes(fill=Damage.Type, x = EVTYPE, y = value))
f+geom_col(position = "stack") + 
     geom_text(data=longHumanStormData, aes(label = n, y=-0.08),
          size=2.5)+
     labs(title = "Human Damage by Event Type", 
          subtitle = "Ranked by number of events per type",
          x = "Event Type" )+
     annotate("label",x = 52, y = -0.08, label = "N", size = 3)+
     coord_flip()

g <- ggplot(longEconStormData, aes(fill=Damage.Type, x = EVTYPE, y = value))
g + geom_col(position = "stack") +

In terms of human damage, tornadoes have the highest impact in both injuries and deaths, whereas one event each which were “UNSEASONABLY WARM AND DRY” and “Heat Wave” had the highest impacts per individual event. In terms of total economic damage, FLOOD has the highest impact on property damage DROUGHT has the highest impact on crop damage. Again one event each had the highest impact on a per-event basis: “HEAVY RAIN/SEVERE WEATHER” on property damage and “EXCESSIVE WETNESS” on crop damage.

It is notable that many of the “Per Event” values are high in events that are representing event types with only one incident. A larger project to properly categorize those into larger event types would likely be useful. For example “Heat Wave”, which is a category with only one event, shows the highest number of injuries per event, but should likely be averaged into the “HEAT” category (which should both likely be averaged into “EXCESSIVE HEAT”, etc.).
